Finding a Median via the CDF






Median of a Random Variable \(X\)



The median of a random variable \(X\) with some CDF \(F_X(v_X)\) is the [set of] numbers \(m\) for which the probability that \(X\) is lower than \(m\) is \(\frac{1}{2}\):
\[
\begin{align*}
\text{Median}(X) &= \left\{m \left| F_X(m) = \frac{1}{2} \right. \right\} \\
&= \left\{m \left| \int_{-\infty}^{m}f_X(v_X)dv_X = \frac{1}{2} \right. \right\}
\end{align*}
\]




(In case you‚Äôre wondering why we start with the median rather than the more commonly-used mean: it‚Äôs specifically because I want you to get used to calculating general functions \(f(X)\) of a random variable \(X\). It‚Äôs easy to just e.g.¬†learn how to compute the mean \(\expect{X}\) and forget that this is only one of many possible choices for \(f(X)\).)

